# Fluff Date: 2026-02-11 15:11:17
overview:<p>The Daedalus is a 45-ton Solaris VII arena BattleMech developed by Innovative Design Concepts from the chassis of an original PXH-1 Phoenix Hawk. First appearing in the arenas during the mid-3050s, the design was originally built around a combination of missile racks and a large pulse laser, leveraging the Phoenix Hawk's renowned speed and maneuverability to keep opponents at arm's length. Though the Daedalus initially proved competitive in the Solaris circuits, advancing technology steadily eroded its edge over rival designs. Rather than abandon their flagship product, IDC undertook a comprehensive overhaul in the early 3060s, replacing the original missile-based armament with an all-energy weapons suite built around experimental pulse technology. The revamped design returned the Daedalus to prominence among Solaris stables, though its specialized arena heritage and the heavily modified Phoenix Hawk frame have limited its appeal outside the Game World.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Daedalus retains the Phoenix Hawk's Earthwerks PXH II endo steel frame and Hermes 270 XL engine, providing a top speed of 97 kilometers per hour. Six Rawlings 45 jump jets give the 'Mech excellent maneuverability in the tight confines of Solaris arenas, allowing leaps of up to 180 meters. The integration of Triple Strength Myomer pushes the design's speed to nearly 119 kilometers per hour when the MechWarrior allows heat to build, a tactic that rewards aggressive energy-weapon use.</p><p>The upgraded DAD-3D mounts a Tronel XIV-EXP large X-Pulse laser as its primary weapon, supported by four RAMTech 1500Z extended-range medium lasers and two Magna Mk IV extended-range small lasers. A Dalban HiRez III Advanced Fire Control System links the entire battery through a targeting computer, dramatically improving accuracy at the cost of additional weight and complexity. Twelve double heat sinks struggle to dissipate the considerable thermal output of this all-energy loadout, though this limitation is deliberately exploited by experienced pilots to trigger the Triple Strength Myomer. Durallex Light armor provides reasonable protection for a medium chassis, though the design's reliance on an XL engine means torso breaches can prove catastrophic.</p>

deployment:<p>This variant strips the large X-Pulse laser and three of the four extended-range medium lasers, replacing them with a pair of Streak SRM-4 launchers and a single Streak SRM-6 launcher. A supercharger-enhanced engine provides burst speed capability at the expense of one and a half tons of armor. The combination of Streak missile systems and TSM-enhanced speed creates an aggressive close-range brawler, though the reduced armor protection demands a hit-and-run approach to survive sustained exchanges.</p>

history:<p>The Daedalus emerged from Innovative Design Concepts' workshop on Solaris VII during the early 3050s, one of numerous Phoenix Hawk derivatives to appear as the Solaris arena circuit adapted to the influx of Clan Invasion-era technology. IDC, a small Solaris City-based firm, specialized in extensively customizing existing chassis rather than developing original designs, and the Daedalus exemplified this approach, a PXH-1 Phoenix Hawk rebuilt from the ground up with an arena-optimized weapons configuration.</p><p>The original DAD-3C found initial success in the mid-3050s circuits, but the rapid pace of technological advancement during the Clan Invasion era quickly eroded its competitive advantage. By the early 3060s, IDC recognized the design required more than incremental improvements, and the company invested in a complete weapons refit that produced the DAD-3D in 3062. The upgraded variant's all-energy loadout and experimental X-Pulse laser technology brought the Daedalus back to the forefront of Solaris competition, with Blackstar Stables adopting it as a signature machine.</p><p>IDC continued to iterate on the platform through the Civil War era, producing the DAD-4A and DAD-4B variants by 3067. The company's leadership harbored ambitions of breaking into mainstream military production markets, even securing a listing on the Lyran Alliance stock exchanges, an unusual distinction for a Solaris design firm. However, the Jihad devastated the Solaris gaming world and effectively ended Daedalus production. IDC survived the conflict but struggled to compete with larger manufacturers in the post-war landscape.</p><p>The firm made one final attempt to revitalize the Daedalus line in 3097 with the DAD-DX prototype, an extravagant experimental variant that consumed over ninety million C-bills in development costs. The prototype's catastrophic arena debut at Hartford Gardens Arena ended the project and any remaining ambitions for the design's revival. By the Dark Age, Solaris VII itself had changed hands multiple times, and the facility that once produced the Daedalus passed from Lyran to Clan Wolf control alongside the rest of the Game World.</p>

